### [High] Wrong Default Enum Value Allows Any Address to Collect a Free NFT

**Affected Files:** src/SantasList.sol

**Description**

In Solidity, the default value of any enum is its first member (index 0). The Status enum is declared with NICE as its first member, meaning every address defaults to Status.NICE — including addresses Santa has never reviewed.

```solidity
@> enum Status {
@>     NICE,        // index 0 — default for ALL unset addresses
       EXTRA_NICE,
       NAUGHTY,
       NOT_CHECKED_TWICE
   }

   function collectPresent() external {
@>     if (s_theList[msg.sender] == Status.NICE || s_theList[msg.sender] == Status.EXTRA_NICE) {
           // ...mint present
       }
   }
```

**Risk**

- Every address defaults to NICE — the vulnerable state is the starting state of the contract.
- Anyone can mint a present without ever being added to Santa's list.

**Impact**

- The entire access-control model is broken at the default-value level.
- The NFT supply can be fully drained by bots before legitimate users claim.

**Proof of Concept**

```solidity
function test_DefaultNiceAllowsFreeNFT() public {
    address stranger = makeAddr("stranger");
    assertEq(uint256(santasList.s_theList(stranger)), uint256(SantasList.Status.NICE));

    vm.warp(santasList.CHRISTMAS_2023_BLOCK_TIME() + 1);
    vm.prank(stranger);
    santasList.collectPresent();

    assertEq(santasList.balanceOf(stranger), 1);
}
```

**Recommended Mitigation**

```diff
  enum Status {
+     NOT_CHECKED_TWICE,  // index 0 — safe default
      NICE,
      EXTRA_NICE,
-     NOT_CHECKED_TWICE,
      NAUGHTY
  }
```

